[1] Philippines
Date: Mon 12 Mar 2018
Source: Malaya Business Insight [edited]
http://www.malaya.com.ph/business-news/news/measles-cases-triple-2018


The number of measles cases in the country almost tripled in the 1st 5 weeks of the year [2018], compared to the same period last year [2017], according to the Department of Health.

According to the latest Measles Disease Surveillance Report, 877 measles cases were recorded from 1 Jan-3 Feb 2018, with 12 deaths.

In the same period last year [2016], 293 measles cases were recorded.

Measles outbreaks were recently been declared in Zamboanga, Davao, Taguig cities and in 7 towns of Negros Oriental.

The DOH said one of the factors in the measles outbreaks could be the refusal of parents to have their children immunized due to the scare brought about by the Dengvaxia scandal.

The latest measles reports showed the areas with the highest number of measles cases are the Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao [ARRM] with 249, Zamboanga Peninsula with 210, and Davao Region with 151.

There were 12 deaths reported -- 6 in the Davao region, 5 in the ARMM, and 1 in the Soccsksargen region.

Children aged 1-4 years old are most affected, at 39.79 percent, followed by infants below 9 months old at 18.70 percent, and infants 9 --11 months old at 9.9 percent.

At least 3 in every 5 cases, or 62 percent, were children who have not been vaccinated against measles.

The DOH report said among the top reasons for non-immunization were the "mother was busy" (25 percent), child was "not eligible" for vaccination (24 percent), and child was sick (15 percent), and "fear of side effects" of the vaccine. Those whose parents refused immunization for various reasons make up only 1 percent, according to the report.

[Byline: Gerard Naval]

