[2] Australia (Melbourne) ex Malaysia: alert
Date: Tue 13 Mar 2018 11:24 GMT
Source: Daily Mail [edited]
http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-5494425/Measles-alert-passengers-board-AirAsia-Melbourne.html


An Australian man has sparked a measles alert after becoming ill on a flight back to Melbourne [Victoria]. The middle-aged man flew with AirAsia from Kuala Lumpur [Malaysia] and potentially exposed hundreds of passengers with the illness.

A warning was issued by Victoria's health department for those on the AirAsia flight D7214 which landed in Melbourne on Wednesday morning [6 Mar 2018], SBS News reported. 'We are working with airline officials to identify and contact passengers who shared the international flight,' deputy chief health officer Brett Sutton said.

Other people in the airport at the same time could also be at risk of contracting the highly contagious illness.

The viral disease is serious for young children but it can be prevented through vaccination.

Symptoms of measles include a runny nose, red eyes and a cough followed by a rash and fever which can appear three to seven days after first symptoms. The disease can cause serious illness in young children including pneumonia.

This is the 2nd confirmed case of measles for Victoria this month [March 2018]. A measles warning was issued earlier in March after a backpacker contracted the illness and travelled to tourist destinations including Phillip Island, the Great Ocean Road, and St Kilda beach.

In late February [2018] another man in his late 40s visited areas in south Melbourne while he was highly infectious with measles.

Despite recent occurrences, measles are uncommon in Australia due to widespread vaccinations.

[Byline: Emily Pidgeon]

